  "A situation where loan payments do not cover the interest due, causing the unpaid interest to be added to the principal so the balance actually grows": "",
  "Negative amortization occurs when payments are less than the accruing interest, causing the loan balance to increase rather than decrease. This dangerous feature was common in some pre-2008 mortgage products and can lead to owing more than the original loan amount.": "",
  "What does 'front-loaded interest' mean in amortization?": "",
  "Interest is only charged in the first year of the loan": "",
  "The lender charges all interest upfront before the loan begins": "",
  "A disproportionately large share of early loan payments goes toward interest rather than principal because the balance is highest at the beginning": "",
  "Interest is added to the front of each monthly payment statement": "",
  "Because interest is calculated on the outstanding balance, early payments are dominated by interest. On a $200,000 mortgage at 6%, the first payment is 83% interest ($1,000) and only 17% principal ($199). This ratio gradually reverses over the loan term.": "",
